  "prompt": "What are Audio Codecs?",
  "response": "Audio codecs are software or hardware tools that encode and decode digital audio data. They are used to compress audio files to save space and facilitate efficient storage and transmission, while also decompressing them for playback. Codecs are essential for maintaining a balance between audio quality and file size, and they play a crucial role in streaming audio, broadcasting, and digital audio storage.\n\nThere are two main types of audio codecs: \n\n1. **Lossy Codecs**: These codecs compress audio data by removing parts of the audio signal that are less perceived by human ears, resulting in a significant reduction in file size. However, this compression can also lead to a loss of quality. Common lossy audio codecs include:\n   - **MP3 (MPEG Audio Layer III)**: One of the most widely used formats, known for achieving relatively high compression ratios.\n   - **AAC (Advanced Audio Codec)**: Offers better sound quality than MP3 at similar bit rates and is used in many streaming services.\n   - **Ogg Vorbis**: An open-source, patent-free codec known for providing good sound quality at lower bitrates.\n\n2. **Lossless Codecs**: These codecs compress audio data without any loss in quality, retaining the original audio exactly as it was. This makes the files larger compared to lossy formats, but preferable for high-quality audio storage. Common lossless audio codecs include:\n   - **FLAC (Free Lossless Audio Codec)**: Popular for maintaining high fidelity audio and efficient compression.\n   - **ALAC (Apple Lossless Audio Codec)**: Used primarily in Apple devices, it provides compression without losing quality.\n   - **WAV (Waveform Audio File Format)/AIFF (Audio Interchange File Format)**: Usually uncompressed or minimally compressed, preserving complete audio data.\n\nAudio codecs are a fundamental component of various audio applications, from music streaming services and online video platforms to voice calls and podcast distribution. They allow users to enjoy audio content in a manner that balances between quality and practicality in file size.",
